Reasoning: The claim that incidence rates of cervical cancer have increased due to nationwide screening programs based primarily on cytology is strongly refuted by the available evidence. Paper ID 36355784, "The effect of mass screening on incidence and mortality of squamous and adenocarcinoma of cervix uteri," explicitly states that in Finland, following the implementation of a nationwide mass screening program in the mid-1960s, the mean incidence of cervical carcinoma significantly decreased from 15.4 per 10^5 woman-years in the early 1960s to 2.7 per 10^5 woman-years in 1991. This paper concludes that the Finnish mass screening program has been effective. Similarly, Paper ID 25742130, "Mass screening programmes and trends in cervical cancer in Finland and the Netherlands," compares trends in cervical cancer incidence and mortality in Finland and the Netherlands, both of which have national screening programs. This paper reports that incidence and mortality rates have declined in both countries, with a more pronounced decline in Finland. These findings consistently demonstrate a decrease, not an increase, in cervical cancer incidence rates in countries with established cytology-based screening programs.
